  "course_description": "This course draws on classical, modern, and contemporary texts to introduce skills required for reading comparatively across national traditions and academic disciplines with an emphasis on close reading, critical interpretation, and the multiplicity of linguistic traditions around the world. *Note: This course is non-repeatable.",
  "course_notes": "Topic: Theory, Practice, and Imaginary This course focuses on translation as an actual practice and metaphor to inquire into the ethics and politics of literary expression, form, and aesthetics. As we read a range of texts, some of which are translations and some take translation as a theme or use it a metaphor, we will examine translation as a creative, political, and gendered practice and discuss various meanings of translation as fidelity, submission, love, subversion, appropriation, worlding, vernacularization, and self-translation. Our readings will include poetry (Don Mee Choi), short stories (Sandra Cisneros), play (Aimé Césaire) memoir (Eva Hoffman), fiction (Abdulrazzak Gurnah, Han Kang), and critical essays (Gayatri Spivak, Walter Benjamin, Salman Rushdie, Arundhati Roy, and Rosemary Arrojo). To complement theoretical and fictional engagement, students will complete their own translation project.",
